snippet.textDisplay: What always confused me about pulleys is exactly HOW they multiply the force applied to them.  Then I realized that they are essentially just levers, used in class 2 configuration.  Imagine the side of the pulley that is anchored to the static rope as the fulcrum.  The other side is where the force is applied, and the hole in the center is the load.  As one lifts or pulls on the moving side, the "lever" pivots around the opposite side, moving the load (attached to the hole) half the distance, but with twice the force.

snippet.textDisplay: Destin, your section that included getting your Jeep stuck reminded me of a pair of tricks my father taught me about mechanical advantage. Neither use snatch blocks but both are useful if you have a length of chain or, in the case of being stuck a stout rope. Dad had taken a friend and I sledding (and wood hauling...), this is about 1966-7. He drove the old 4x4 out into a flat field that had 8" of powder snow and we set off to buck some birch and do some sledding. Upon our return, we discovered that under all 4 wheels of the truck there was a thick layer of solid ice. Even trying to ease the truck into motion wasn't happening, all 4 wheels were spinning as if the truck was on a hoist. Dad pulls out a length of 1" rope, tied it to the frame (separate lesson on a bowline knot) and instructed me to proceed with the other and to an anchor tree, put a wrap around it and pull it as tight as possible. He got in the truck and instructed my friend to push on the rope at the center of the line between truck & tree at right angles to the line. My buddy was able to push the rope 2-3 feet moving the truck just an inch or two. Dad applied the brakes, my buddy let up on the pressure & I took up the slack at the wrap at the tree. Rinse & repeat until we'd moved the truck a few feet where there was a little traction and we were free. This is the power of trigonometry! The force applied was my 50-60 lb. buddy on an icy surface to the rope, but the force applied (at first) to the truck was perhaps 30 lbs. / sin(~179.9999 degrees) or bunches (>100,000 lbs.)! As the angle drops from ~180, the force drops rapidly too, but a hundred foot rope keeps a high angle to this point for several feet. The other mech advantage trick was using a length of stout chain (35-40 lbs. 10') bolted to a stubborn axel in an old tractor needing removal. Using the mass and momentum of the chain to yank that axel in a couple of tries. I don't miss the cold and snow of Montana, but I do recall lessons well received... :)

At (12:30), that’s actually NOT “exactly what you want”. The pin of the shackle should be facing up, in the block. Not on the line. Also, never stare down a cable, attached to a winch, under load (9:25). Instead stand well away from the cable or anywhere it could fly off in the event of a failure. You really should have a blanket draped over the cable while under load as well. If you’re gonna teach rigging, you might as well teach it right.
🤜🤛

snippet.textDisplay:
The weight is purchased by the distance.... simple they knew that in like 5000 BC... it's the DISTANCE not tension dude... the SAME energy is being expended however by doubling the distance aka the amount of rope you need to LIFT the block you seem to make it easier.... however you still have to WIND up twice as much rope... the thing that pulleys do is PURCHASE WEIGHT with distance- that is the key to what is being done... nothing is free... the block & tackle was invented to reduce the distance that an actual horse, elephant human had to walk rotate wind up on a drum the LENGTH of rope that is purchasing the weight... so it's not about TENSION it's about LENGTH OF ROPE being added so that you reduce the particular energy at a point in time... over time & distance you still expend the SAME energy to lift the rope... the arrangement makes it easier so a human can wind 100 times the amount of rope quickly/easily rather than lift 1 yard of rope with all energy expended in a moment... this is also the reason an impulse force does such damage rather than static loads.... the load is applied in an instant... if you can slow down the applied loading & spread it out you can allow the force to move through rather than into the object... you need to study physics your empirical methods are failing to teach people the principle involved:
YOU PURCHASE the weight with LENGTH of rope... over time if you will... you get 8 lbs on the output through 2 lbs but you need to pull 4 times more rope to get it to same height! Aka do the same work! Also you will notice that the more pulleys you add the less it does the SAME WORK as before aka it is slowly becoming just a straight lever... so it isn't actually lifting any longer it is tilting more than lifting so the motion is no longer a VECTOR UP in the vertical.... thus you see by NOT actually winding up the rope & PAYING for the weight you purchased with DISTANCE you start losing the same work being done.... nothing is free! The weight is purchased by the distance.... simple they knew that in like 5000 BC... it's the DISTANCE not tension dude... the SAME energy is being expended however by doubling the distance aka the amount of rope you need to LIFT the block you seem to make it easier.... however you still have to WIND up twice as much rope... the thing that pulleys do is PURCHASE WEIGHT with distance- that is the key to what is being done... nothing is free... the block & tackle was invented to reduce the distance that an actual horse, elephant human had to walk rotate wind up on a drum the LENGTH of rope that is purchasing the weight... so it's not about TENSION it's about LENGTH OF ROPE being added so that you reduce the particular energy at a point in time... over time & distance you still expend the SAME energy to lift the rope... the arrangement makes it easier so a human can wind 100 times the amount of rope quickly/easily rather than lift 1 yard of rope with all energy expended in a moment... this is also the reason an impulse force does such damage rather than static loads.... the load is applied in an instant... if you can slow down the applied loading & spread it out you can allow the force to move through rather than into the object... you need to study physics your empirical methods are failing to teach people the principle involved:
YOU PURCHASE the weight with LENGTH of rope... over time if you will... you get 8 lbs on the output through 2 lbs but you need to pull 4 times more rope to get it to same height! Aka do the same work! Also you will notice that the more pulleys you add the less it does the SAME WORK as before aka it is slowly becoming just a straight lever... so it isn't actually lifting any longer it is tilting more than lifting so the motion is no longer a VECTOR UP in the vertical.... thus you see by NOT actually winding up the rope & PAYING for the weight you purchased with DISTANCE you start losing the same work being done.... nothing is free! Also we never went to the moon & the pyramids were not built by the egyptians!

snippet.textDisplay:
I did towing and recovery for a little while, and my most-used "non standard" equipment was definitely a snatch block. It opens up so many options. Not only letting you pull harder than your winch could normally do, but pulling from a direction you wouldn't be able to. There are some really neat tricks for a snatch block.


It always impressed me as being one of those tools whose usefulness was basically only limited by how clever you are... and how many you have on hand.

How do you turn 8,000 lbs of pulling force into 16,000? Snatch block!!


How do you pull a car that's stuck in park out of a parking space in a supermarket so you can turn it and load it onto a flat bed? Snatch block!!

How do you haul an 80,000 lb truck out of a ditch and back onto solid ground? Snatch blocks!!
